{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0182oaeFzU1LwyVEjpix2Lek","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Additional Operating Scenarios (predict each)\n2\t\n3\tThese extend the cases in 04. Same facility, same physics. For each scenario predict the\n4\trequested quantities with assumptions and confidence.\n5\t\n6\t## Scenario B1 — Partially blocked riser ducts\n7\tConfiguration: heater at the normal-operation duty (~42 kWe electric, i.e. the 26 kWt-class\n8\tload), natural circulation, a single vertical chimney stack open (the second stack closed).\n9\tProgressively, whole riser ducts are blocked off at their inlets:\n10\t- Stage 0: all 12 ducts open (reference)\n11\t- Stage 1: 2 of 12 ducts blocked (16.7%)\n12\t- Stage 2: 4 of 12 ducts blocked (33.3%)\n13\t- Stage 3: 6 of 12 ducts blocked (50%)\n14\t\n15\tPredict at each stage: total system mass flow rate, riser air temperature rise, and the\n16\theated-plate temperature. In particular: by how much does the plate temperature rise when\n17\tHALF the cooling ducts are lost? Is the degradation graceful or cliff-like?\n18\t\n19\t## Scenario B2 — Heavy-gas ingress\n20\tConfiguration: steady natural circulation at ~42 kWe. Event: a large volume of argon\n21\t(molecular weight 40 vs air 29) is suddenly introduced into the inlet plenum at the bottom\n22\tof the loop, displacing the air there.\n23\t\n24\tPredict: what happens to the natural circulation (magnitude and timescale), what the riser\n25\tgas temperatures do, and whether/when/how the system recovers on its own. Explain the\n26\tmechanism.\n27\t\n28\t## Scenario B3 — Accident transient: summer vs winter\n29\tThe Case-2 decay-heat transient (26 → 56 kWt over ~85 h) is run twice: once with outdoor\n30\tambient averaging ~10 °C (winter) and once averaging ~25 °C (summer), otherwise identical.\n31\t\n32\tPredict the percentage or absolute change (winter → summer) in: system mass flow rate,\n33\triser duct wall temperature, and heated-plate temperature — both at the initial normal load\n34\tand at the decay-heat peak. Which quantity is most weather-sensitive and which is most\n35\tprotected, and why?\n36\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bc9372b2-97b1-470d-9ef7-d9ff285e4e4d","uuid":"53dfe701-269b-4093-886e-622383fdf818","timestamp":"2026-07-01T22:09:20.780Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/blind2/inputs/05_additional_scenarios.md","content":"# Additional Operating Scenarios (predict each)\n\nThese extend the cases in 04. Same facility, same physics. For each scenario predict the\nrequested quantities with assumptions and confidence.\n\n## Scenario B1 — Partially blocked riser ducts\nConfiguration: heater at the normal-operation duty (~42 kWe electric, i.e. the 26 kWt-class\nload), natural circulation, a single vertical chimney stack open (the second stack closed).\nProgressively, whole riser ducts are blocked off at their inlets:\n- Stage 0: all 12 ducts open (reference)\n- Stage 1: 2 of 12 ducts blocked (16.7%)\n- Stage 2: 4 of 12 ducts blocked (33.3%)\n- Stage 3: 6 of 12 ducts blocked (50%)\n\nPredict at each stage: total system mass flow rate, riser air temperature rise, and the\nheated-plate temperature. In particular: by how much does the plate temperature rise when\nHALF the cooling ducts are lost? Is the degradation graceful or cliff-like?\n\n## Scenario B2 — Heavy-gas ingress\nConfiguration: steady natural circulation at ~42 kWe. Event: a large volume of argon\n(molecular weight 40 vs air 29) is suddenly introduced into the inlet plenum at the bottom\nof the loop, displacing the air there.\n\nPredict: what happens to the natural circulation (magnitude and timescale), what the riser\ngas temperatures do, and whether/when/how the system recovers on its own. Explain the\nmechanism.\n\n## Scenario B3 — Accident transient: summer vs winter\nThe Case-2 decay-heat transient (26 → 56 kWt over ~85 h) is run twice: once with outdoor\nambient averaging ~10 °C (winter) and once averaging ~25 °C (summer), otherwise identical.\n\nPredict the percentage or absolute change (winter → summer) in: system mass flow rate,\nriser duct wall temperature, and heated-plate temperature — both at the initial normal load\nand at the decay-heat peak. Which quantity is most weather-sensitive and which is most\nprotected, and why?\n","numLines":36,"startLine":1,"totalLines":36}}}
